  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Statin therapy does not fully eliminate the cardiovascular disease (CVD) risk associated with
      low high density lipoprotein-C (HDL-C) and high triglyceride levels. It is currently unknown
      what would be the best treatment option for patients with mixed hyperlipidemia who fail to
      meet their lipid targets with statin monotherapy at conventional does, i.e. high dose
      rosuvastatin or conventional statin dose plus micronized fenofibrate or conventional statin
      dose plus niacin/laropiprant. The aim of the present study is to compare the efficacy of
      high-dose rosuvastatin vs conventional statin dose plus micronized fenofibrate vs
      conventional statin dose plus extended-release niacin/laropiprant on lipid profile in
      patients with mixed hyperlipidemia. The primary efficacy endpoint will be changes in
      non-HDL-C levels at 6 months after treatment initiation.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
